******
[2] Media report
Date: Fri 2 Jan 2014
Source: South China Morning Post [edited]
http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1672918/hong-kong-could-ban-live-poultry-sales-amid-h7n9-bird-flu-scare-says


Live poultry sales could be banned in the city if industry workers failed to consider the public interest amid a bird flu scare, Secretary for Food and Health Dr Ko Wing-man said.

His remarks come as wholesalers argue with the government over delivery arrangements for local live poultry, following the culling of
19 000 birds at Cheung Sha Wan wholesale market and a 3-week embargo on imported birds after samples from a farm in Huizhou, Guangdong tested positive for the deadly H7N9 strain of the virus.

9 local poultry wholesalers are threatening to cease trading until imports resume unless the government rethinks an arrangement under which all local chickens are gathered for inspection at Ta Kwu Ling [New Territories, Hong Kong] while the Cheung Sha Wan market is closed under the ban.

Ko said this morning [2 Jan 2014] that the government is unable to arrange another site to replace the new checkpoint, which is too small to allow traders to offload chickens from trucks for distribution to different vehicles bound for wet markets across the city.

"The city relies on the strict measures in the live poultry supply chain to prevent the public from the threat of bird flu," Ko said. "If the industry workers do not put aside [their self interest], I believe in the long term it is up to the public to decide whether to end the live poultry supply."

The government has employed consultants to study whether live poultry supplies should be stopped, Ko said. He stressed it is important that birds are moved directly from farm to retailer without mixing with other chickens, so the government can trace the supply chain. Ko urged wholesalers to alter their current logistics or use smaller delivery trucks to solve the problem.

But a live poultry wholesalers association said the government should allow them to offload live chickens and move them to different trucks for delivery to retailers. They threaten to stage a protest on [Sun 4 Jan 2014] if the government fails to respond to their demand.

In January last year [2014], 20 000 birds were culled and all live chicken sales banned for 3 weeks after a sample from a Guangdong supplier tested positive for bird flu. Both mainland and local sales were halted as Cheung Sha Wan wholesale market was closed for disinfection. The government paid more than HKD 10 million [about USD 1.3 million] in compensation to affected breeders and wholesalers.

Chief Executive Leung Chun-ying said at the time that the affair raised questions over whether live poultry sales could continue in the city.
But local industry workers complained that the government had damaged their business and demanded a second site to allow the sale of local chickens. Responding to their demand, the government opened a new checkpoint on old farmland at Ta Kwu Ling a few months ago. Ko said it could be used to process chickens from local farms while the block on mainland imports remained.

[Byline: Emily Tsang]

