Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[After detecting infection in a single sample (out of 120 or 1200 sampled?) the authorities have opted, as a precautionary preventive measure, to apply the stamping-out policy to all birds which were kept in the market and could have been exposed to the zoonotic LPAI H7N9 virus, namely chickens, chukars (a domesticated partridge species; see picture at http://tinyurl.com/n3v2s3c), and pigeons.

The veterinary authorities of Hong Kong (SAR-PRC) maintain already for several years a commendable, systematic prevention and control policy addressing the possible introduction of avian influenza and other zoonotic disease agents from the mainland. The policy includes periodical "free days" enabling disinfection of the market premises and facilities, as well as requirements for pre-export testing of the poultry consignments being conditional for permitting their transport from the mainland, and testing of representative samples upon arrival.

Could the recent discovery of LPAI H7N9 been viewed by them as a potential deficiency in the mainland's testing regime?

The zoonotic H7N9 virus strain responsible for human infections in China has been reported from Eastern China since March 2013, circulating mostly on live poultry markets. This virus strain is of low pathogenicity in poultry (LPAI H7N9), which means the disease symptoms in birds are slight or absent (=subclinical). The birds are, in fact, the reservoir of the virus without becoming sick, their being infected discovered only by tests applied in apparently healthy animals, or -- as seen multiple times -- following human infection, humans playing the unfortunate role of virus sentinels.

According to Chinese sources, between 22 and 27 Dec 2014, human H7N9 cases were reported in Xinijiang (7 new cases), in Hong Kong (ex Guangdong, one case), in Zhejiang (4 cases, 2 deaths), and in Jiangsu (1 case, who died).

China's last report to the OIE on H7N9 detected in (tested) poultry, dates back to 9 Jul 2014 (see, with map of all "outbreaks", most of them discovered on live animal markets, not on farms, at http://tinyurl.com/kdu3zxo).

OIE's Q&A on LPAI H7N9 is available at http://www.oie.int/en/for-the-media/press-releases/detail/article/questions-and-answers-on-influenza-ah7n9/. China's Ministry of Agriculture LPAI H7N9 information is available in Chinese at http://www.moa.gov.cn/sjzz/syj/dwyqdt/. - Mod.AS

Maps of China can be seen at http://www.sacu.org/maps/provmap.png and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3067796,198. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
